  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the Tower of Seeking Benevolence
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: 'Those in the world who exhaust the pleasures of sightseeing must exhaust themselves traversing the secluded depths of mountains and waters, crossing the vast expanse of wild fields, wearing out spirit and laboring bone, only then to gain a joy that amounts to nothing more than delighting the eye with the scenery before them, indulging the pleasures of a moment. When joy reaches its peak and passes, in the blink of an eye it becomes dim as old traces, like a dream from last night that leaves no mark. Some have obtained estates near the capital, like the Green Fields Lodge of Pei Du or the country villa of Xie An—yet this is truly difficult to attain. Some achieve it only in their declining years after leaving office, others in times of national crisis. Later seekers of such things cannot help but sigh deeply over this. Yet our Minister Yun, encountering a time of national leisure, entered the Central Secretariat in his youth to share in affairs of state. He chose land at the southeast corner of the capital and built a simple thatched dwelling to reside in. Mountains luxuriantly embrace it from without; clear spring waters flow forth from within. He further raised a new tower to the east of his house. Daily he receives guests, and together they drink wine and compose poems upon the tower. Thus, without abandoning his position as minister, he possesses the thoughts of a recluse transcending the dust of the world. Without stepping beyond his gate and courtyard, he peacefully enjoys the pleasures of wandering mountains and waters. Is not this the very meaning of the saying: "How distant is benevolence? When I seek it, it arrives at once"? How could one doubt this? Confucius also said: "The benevolent one loves mountains." Therefore, let us call this tower the Tower of Seeking Benevolence. As for the greatness of the Way of Benevolence and the means of pursuing it, these surely lie in our own earnest effort. Meeting you in days to come, I shall surely see you with new eyes.'
  footnotes:
    - Pei Du (裵度, 765-839) and Xie An (謝安, 320-385) were renowned statesmen of ancient China known for their literary refinement and estates—historical exemplars of cultivated officials.
    - 'The phrase quoted is from Confucius: "Humanity is not far away; when I seek it, it is at hand." This expresses the paradox that virtue, though seemingly distant, becomes present through sincere pursuit.'
    - 'The tower''s name plays on the homophone: 求仁 (seeking benevolence) echoes the philosophical concept of pursuing moral cultivation rather than mere physical escape from the world.'
